        <body>
            <head>170. Memorandum From the Special Advisor to the President and Secretary of State
                on Arms Control Matters (<persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName>) to
                Secretary of State <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d170fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Lot 90D397, Ambassador <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName>’s
                    Personal Files 1953, 1972–1989, Box 8, Binder—Bkgnd for Vienna Mtg. Secret;
                        <gloss target="#t_NODIS_1">Nodis</gloss>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1986-10-31"
                        >October 31, 1986</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Admiral <persName corresp="recusSiT3UbixAWkn">Crowe</persName>’s Reaction to
                    the Draft Vienna Talking Points</item>
            </list>
            <p>I saw Admiral <persName corresp="recusSiT3UbixAWkn">Crowe</persName> at 4:00 p.m.,
                Thursday, October 30th. I said that you were anxious to get his thoughts on the
                talking points we had prepared for your use in your talk with <persName
                    corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName> on <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                </gloss> issues in Vienna.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d170fn2">The talking
                    points were not found. <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                    and <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName>’s meetings in
                    Vienna, November 5–6, are printed in <ref target="frus1981-88v06#d6">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, volume VI,
                        Soviet Union, October 1986–January 1989, Documents 6</ref> and <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v06#d7">7</ref>.</note> He read the talking points and
                commented as he went along. He said that numbers in the proposal seemed consistent
                with his understanding of where we were. His concern was specifically with the
                10-year period as it affected the elimination of either <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>, <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec9Bd6LsNR8IHKv5">offensive strategic systems</rs>, or <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recqBa61v9UU0I2bD">nuclear weapons</rs>. He pointed out
                that if we abided by the restriction in the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> throughout
                the 10-year period we would be in no position to deploy advanced <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs">defenses</rs> in less than
                another 3–4 years even if all the technology would have been proven out earlier. He
                expressed surprise and resentment that after <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs> no one at the White House had asked
                him for the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Chiefs</orgName>’ view as to
                whether we had “sold the store.” He said that the <pb facs="0787" n="760"
                    xml:id="pg_760"/> work that led up to his comments at the <orgName
                    corresp="rec7JKzsWH5H30emC">NSPG</orgName>
                <note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d170fn3">See <ref target="#d168">Document
                    168</ref>.</note> had been purely at his own initiative. He said that after the
                    <orgName corresp="rec7JKzsWH5H30emC">NSPG</orgName> meeting, <persName
                    corresp="rec6rjfFsKmuW0bbp">Poindexter</persName> had telephoned him and had
                protested that what he had said was not helpful in carrying out the <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">President</persName>’s decision.</p>
            <p>He made a particular point of the fact that today the sole mission of the Soviet’s
                submarine fleet, and in fact of their entire <orgName corresp="recqa7xyfbs1XQfVZ"
                    >Navy</orgName>, is to protect their <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBMs</rs>
                </gloss>. If <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBMs</rs>
                </gloss> were to be eliminated, their 340 submarines and other Naval assets would be
                devoted to other purposes, making our Naval tasks complicated. He also emphasized
                the necessity of preserving <rs corresp="recMrVNgNJpQ8DjcR" type="topic"
                    >deterrence</rs> phase by phase.</p>
            <p>I asked him whether a longer time-period for elimination of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>, say 12 years, would be
                better from the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Chiefs</orgName>’ standpoint.
                He suggested one might leave the <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recXrGW53dEgm0PM4">nonwithdrawal</rs> from the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1"
                    >ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> at 10 years
                and provide for the elimination of <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04"
                    >ballistic missiles</rs> over a somewhat longer period of time—say 12 years.
                This would leave a lesser gap in time. I suggested that one might also reduce the
                time gap by proceeding earlier to deploy a limited <gloss target="#t_ABM_1"
                    >ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs">defense</rs> at Grand Forks,
                ND. This would give one experience with the operational deployment of at least one
                element of an advanced <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs"
                    >defense</rs>. I suggested one also might proceed with development and
                deployment of anti-<rs type="topic" corresp="recK1EADTOkzzqeeI">tactical</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>, or <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs">defense</rs> permitted under
                the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs>. He thought
                this was a constructive suggestion.</p>
            <p>I asked him whether the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Chiefs</orgName> would
                approve a program for the second five-years which would result in a further
                reduction of 90% in <rs type="topic" corresp="rec9Bd6LsNR8IHKv5">offensive strategic
                    systems</rs>; i.e., leaving no more than 600 <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RVs</gloss>
                plus long-range <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss>. He said he was confident that the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah"
                    >Chiefs</orgName> would back such an alternative.</p>
            <p>I did not leave the talking points with him.</p>
        </body>
